    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading about bread and saw the term maillard reaction. can u explain what that actually is and what temp it usually happens at? i keep getting confused between that and caramelization.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Maillard reaction is a chemical process between amino acids and reducing sugars that creates browned, savory flavors, differing from the sweeter caramelization which only occurs between sugars alone. It typically begins around 140–165°C (284–330°F), making it perfect for searing meats or baking bread crusts before the food becomes too hot for its structural integrity. You can tell them apart by noticing that Maillard reactions dominated by proteins produce umami notes, whereas caramelization relies purely on sugar breakdown to create nutty and toasty flavors.",
